'new economy' continue to be widely debated. As firms reorganise work and seek to minimise labour 

costs in the recessionary context, 'flexibility' for many workers has come to mean increased workloads, 

less predictable schedules, and more unsocial work hours. Household life has also become more 

complex with more dual earner and lone-parent households, decline of the extended family, and 

greater eldercare responsibilities in the context of increased life expectancy. Simultaneously, the 

neoliberal attack on social provisioning has transferred the burden of care down to the 'natural' level 

of home where most women retain major responsibility for the everyday activities of social 

reproduction. The overall result is an ongoing, complex, gendered, multi-variable balancing act 

between the competing demands of paid work and responsibilities, commitments and life interests 

beyond the workplace, for which workers have only finite time and energy.

